      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 5 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Should You Move Out Before Selling Your Home in Brisbane?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Moving out is not always the right call, but it can change how buyers experience your property. Here is how to think through the decision.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The question of whether to move out before selling comes up in almost every pre-sale conversation. There is no single right answer. Most vendors in Brisbane's inner east sell their home while still living in it, and many achieve excellent results. But there are circumstances where vacating the property before the campaign starts gives you a genuine advantage in how buyers experience and respond to it. Working out which situation you are in is a more useful exercise than assuming one approach is always better than the other.</p>

      <p>The more important underlying question is not whether the home is occupied, but whether you can present it consistently and compellingly throughout the campaign. That question has a different answer depending on the property, the household, and the vendor's capacity to manage the process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The case for staying in your home while it sells</h2>
      <p>Selling while still living in the property is the default for good reasons. It avoids the cost and disruption of temporary accommodation. It avoids the carrying cost of running two households simultaneously, which for a four-to-six week campaign in Brisbane can amount to several thousand dollars. It allows you to remain close to the property through the campaign and manage any issues that arise without the friction of being elsewhere.</p>

      <p>There is also a presentation argument for staying. An occupied home has furniture in place, which helps buyers understand the scale and liveability of the space in a way that an empty property does not. Buyers looking at a vacant home are often trying to mentally furnish it during the inspection, which is cognitive work that distracts from the features of the property itself. A furnished home, presented well, gives buyers a complete picture.</p>

      <p>Owner-occupied homes in Brisbane's inner east also carry a sense of care and maintenance that buyers sometimes respond to positively. A home that is clearly loved and maintained, with fresh paint, tended gardens, and clean surfaces, can convey a level of upkeep that an empty property with its flat-pack staging cannot. The lived-in quality can work in your favour if the home presents well.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When moving out makes sense</h2>
      <p>Moving out is worth considering when the property is genuinely difficult to present in its occupied state. Some situations make this clear. If the household is large and active, with young children, pets, or significant amounts of furniture and personal belongings, achieving the level of consistent presentation that drives strong buyer responses can be very difficult while living there. Open homes every Saturday and private inspections mid-week for four to six weeks is a sustained demand, and the stress on the household can affect the quality of the campaign.</p>

      <p>Properties that benefit most from professional styling are also strong candidates for vacating. When a stylist can take full control of the interior, the result is typically more coherent and considered than styling overlaid on the vendor's existing furniture. A property where the existing furnishings are dated, idiosyncratic in colour, or simply not the right scale for the rooms will almost always present better with a full style than a partial one.</p>

      <p>If your personal circumstances mean you are relocating for work or have already purchased your next property and have flexibility about when to move, the case for vacating early is straightforward. You remove the campaign management burden and give the property its best presentation opportunity at the same time.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Professional styling as the middle ground</h2>
      <p>For many vendors, the practical answer sits between a full vacant and a fully occupied campaign. A good property stylist can work with an occupied home by supplementing or replacing key pieces, clearing specific rooms, and creating a considered presentation even if the vendor is still living there. The cost of styling an occupied home is typically lower than a full vacant styling, because the stylist is working with existing furniture rather than bringing in a full furniture package.</p>

      <p>The key to making this work is a genuine pre-sale declutter. The single most reliable pre-sale action for owner-occupied properties is removing excess furniture and personal items before the photographer arrives and the campaign begins. Buyers walking through an open home are forming an impression quickly, and they are measuring the space with their eyes. A room with forty percent less furniture reads as larger and more flexible than the same room fully furnished, even if the difference is not dramatic.</p>

      <p>Storage facilities are available throughout Brisbane's inner east, and a short-term storage arrangement for the campaign period is a relatively low cost compared to the upside of a cleaner, more spacious presentation. Your agent can usually recommend a styling consultant who can walk through the property before you list and identify specifically what to move, what to keep, and what to replace.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Managing open homes as an owner-occupier</h2>
      <p>The standard approach in Brisbane is for the vendor to leave the property for every open home and private inspection. Buyers are more candid and comfortable when the owner is not present, and your agent can have more productive conversations with potential buyers without the dynamic of you being in the room. This is not a reflection on you: it is simply how buyers behave, and working with that reality rather than against it produces better outcomes.</p>

      <p>Pets require particular attention. Dogs and cats can significantly affect the buyer experience, through smell, hair, or simply by being present during an inspection. Making arrangements for pets to be off the property for opens is important and something to plan for before the campaign starts, not manage reactively on open home day.</p>

      <p>Consistency matters throughout a campaign. The first buyers through the door on the first Saturday set the tone for what your marketing photographs and agent communications have promised. If the property is clean, well-presented, and aired on the first open, maintaining that standard through the following weeks sustains buyer confidence and supports your negotiating position on price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The decision in practice</h2>
      <p>Work through the specific situation honestly rather than defaulting to either approach. Ask whether you can consistently present the property at a high standard for the duration of the campaign while living there. Ask whether the existing furniture and personal style of the home will help or hinder how buyers see themselves in the space. Ask whether your household circumstances (children, pets, shift work, health) make the sustained demand of a campaign genuinely manageable.</p>

      <p>If the answers suggest the home will present better vacant, and you have a practical option to make that happen, moving out is probably worth the cost and effort. If the answers suggest a well-managed occupied campaign is achievable, save your resources and focus them on preparation and presentation quality.</p>

      <div style="padding:1.5rem;background:rgba(245,208,122,0.06);border-left:3px solid #f5d07a;">
